                         "body":  "\u003c!-- Generated by sourcery-ai[bot]: start review_guide --\u003e\n\n## Reviewer\u0027s Guide\n\nIntroduces a dedicated performance testing infrastructure by adding BenchmarkDotNet harnesses for core hot paths, lockГ”ГҮГҰfree unit tests around FSM/actor and order management patterns, and zeroГ”ГҮГҰallocation NinjaTrader API mocks, all wired through new test and benchmark projects.\n\n#### Sequence diagram for running Benchmarks via Program.Main\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    actor Developer\n    participant Program\n    participant BenchmarkSwitcher\n    participant BarUpdateBenchmark\n    participant OrderCallbacksBenchmark\n    participant SIMADispatchBenchmark\n\n    Developer-\u003e\u003eProgram: Main(args)\n    Program-\u003e\u003eBenchmarkSwitcher: FromAssembly(typeof(Program).Assembly)\n    BenchmarkSwitcher--\u003e\u003eProgram: BenchmarkSwitcher\n    Program-\u003e\u003eBenchmarkSwitcher: Run(args)\n    BenchmarkSwitcher-\u003e\u003eBarUpdateBenchmark: execute benchmarks\n    BenchmarkSwitcher-\u003e\u003eOrderCallbacksBenchmark: execute benchmarks\n    BenchmarkSwitcher-\u003e\u003eSIMADispatchBenchmark: execute benchmarks\n```\n\n### File-Level Changes\n\n| Change | Details | Files |\n| ------ | ------- | ----- |\n| Add lock-free order management unit tests with an in-memory concurrent tracker to validate lifecycle, concurrency, and state transitions. | \u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eCreate OrderManagementTests covering state transitions, concurrent tracking, atomic quantity updates, idempotent cancellation, and atomic price modifications\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eImplement MockOrderTracker using ConcurrentDictionary and Interlocked operations to simulate lock-free order management\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eDefine OrderData storage type to hold per-order state, filled quantity, and limit price\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e | `tests/V12_Performance.Tests/Core/OrderManagementTests.cs` |\n| Add FSM/actor pattern unit tests and a mock actor implementation to validate queueing, ordering, and atomic state transitions under concurrency. | \u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eCreate FSMActorTests to cover single/multiple message processing, concurrent producers, atomic state transitions, and high-throughput ordering guarantees\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eImplement MockFSMActor using ConcurrentQueue and Interlocked operations to provide a lock-free enqueue/process model\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eDefine MockMessage data type to represent actor messages used across tests\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e | `tests/V12_Performance.Tests/Core/FSMActorTests.cs` |\n| Introduce zero-allocation NinjaTrader-like mocks as struct-based value types for use across tests and benchmarks. | \u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eDefine IBar, IOrder, IExecution, and IAccount interfaces to abstract NinjaTrader dependencies\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eImplement MockBar, MockOrder, MockExecution, and MockAccount as structs to avoid heap allocation during tests and benchmarks\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eAdd OrderState enum mirroring NinjaTrader order lifecycle states for consistent semantics\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e | `tests/V12_Performance.Tests/Mocks/INinjaTraderMocks.cs` |\n| Add BenchmarkDotNet harnesses for OnBarUpdate, order callback, and SIMA dispatch hot paths using the new zero-allocation mocks. | \u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eImplement BarUpdateBenchmark with benchmarks for bar update hot path, bar data access, and account state checks using MockBar, MockAccount, and MockOrder\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eImplement OrderCallbacksBenchmark with benchmarks for order update, execution update, order state transitions, and PnL calculations using mock types\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eImplement SIMADispatchBenchmark with benchmarks for SIMA dispatch logic, state checks, message enqueue semantics, and price proximity calculations\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eShare struct-based mocks from the test assembly to keep benchmarks allocation-free\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e | `benchmarks/BarUpdateBenchmark.cs`\u003cbr/\u003e`benchmarks/OrderCallbacksBenchmark.cs`\u003cbr/\u003e`benchmarks/SIMADispatchBenchmark.cs` |\n| Add a BenchmarkDotNet console entry point and separate benchmark/test project configurations to host the new infrastructure. | \u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eCreate a Program entry point that uses BenchmarkSwitcher to discover and run all benchmarks in the benchmarks assembly\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eAdd a dedicated benchmarks project file configured for BenchmarkDotNet runs\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eAdd a test project file to host the new unit tests and mocks\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e | `benchmarks/Program.cs`\u003cbr/\u003e`benchmarks/V12_Performance.Benchmarks.csproj`\u003cbr/\u003e`tests/V12_Performance.Tests/V12_Performance.Tests.csproj` |\n\n---\n\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003eTips and commands\u003c/summary\u003e\n\n#### Interacting with Sourcery\n\n- **Trigger a new review:** Comment `@sourcery-ai review` on the pull request.\n- **Continue discussions:** Reply directly to Sourcery\u0027s review comments.\n- **Generate a GitHub issue from a review comment:** Ask Sourcery to create an\n  issue from a review comment by replying to it. You can also reply to a\n  review comment with `@sourcery-ai issue` to create an issue from it.\n- **Generate a pull request title:** Write `@sourcery-ai` anywhere in the pull\n  request title to generate a title at any time. You can also comment\n  `@sourcery-ai title` on the pull request to (re-)generate the title at any time.\n- **Generate a pull request summary:** Write `@sourcery-ai summary` anywhere in\n  the pull request body to generate a PR summary at any time exactly where you\n  want it. You can also comment `@sourcery-ai summary` on the pull request to\n  (re-)generate the summary at any time.\n- **Generate reviewer\u0027s guide:** Comment `@sourcery-ai guide` on the pull\n  request to (re-)generate the revi