                        "body":  "Hey - I\u0027ve found 3 issues, and left some high level feedback:\n\n- In `MockOrderTracker.CancelOrder`, the `Interlocked.CompareExchange` is operating on a local `currentState` value rather than shared state, so the compare/exchange is not actually atomic or preventing multiple successful cancellations; consider storing the state as an `int` field on `OrderData` (or a separate shared field) and performing `CompareExchange` directly against that field.\n- The benchmarks currently depend on types from the `V12_Performance.Tests.Mocks` namespace; you may want to move these mocks (or a subset) into a shared library or production project to avoid benchmarks taking a hard dependency on the test assembly and to keep layering cleaner.\n\n\u003cdetails\u003e\n\u003csummary\u003ePrompt for AI Agents\u003c/summary\u003e\n\n~~~markdown\nPlease address the comments from this code review:\n\n## Overall Comments\n- In `MockOrderTracker.CancelOrder`, the `Interlocked.CompareExchange` is operating on a local `currentState` value rather than shared state, so the compare/exchange is not actually atomic or preventing multiple successful cancellations; consider storing the state as an `int` field on `OrderData` (or a separate shared field) and performing `CompareExchange` directly against that field.\n- The benchmarks currently depend on types from the `V12_Performance.Tests.Mocks` namespace; you may want to move these mocks (or a subset) into a shared library or production project to avoid benchmarks taking a hard dependency on the test assembly and to keep layering cleaner.\n\n## Individual Comments\n\n### Comment 1\n\u003clocation path=\"benchmarks/SIMADispatchBenchmark.cs\" line_range=\"45-54\" /\u003e\n\u003ccode_context\u003e\n+            };\n+        }\n+\n+        [Benchmark]\n+        public void OnBarUpdate_HotPath()\n+        {\n\u003c/code_context\u003e\n\u003cissue_to_address\u003e\n**issue (performance):** Benchmark body is likely to be optimized away because computed values are unused and the guard is never triggered with the current setup.\n\nIn `SIMA_Dispatch_HotPath`, the intermediate flags (`isWorking`, `hasPnL`, `shouldFlatten`, `shouldCancel`) are computed but never used, and the exception path is unreachable with the current inputs. This lets the JIT/BenchmarkDotNet treat most of the method as dead code, so the benchmark wonГ”ГҮГ–t represent the real hot-path cost. Please make the work observable (e.g., via `Consumer.Consume`/`Blackhole` or a `volatile` field) and adjust the guard so it canГ”ГҮГ–t be constant-folded for the fixed inputs.\n\u003c/issue_to_address\u003e\n\n### Comment 2\n\u003clocation path=\"benchmarks/SIMADispatchBenchmark.cs\" line_range=\"108-115\" /\u003e\n\u003ccode_context\u003e\n+        }\n+\n+        [Benchmark]\n+        public void SIMA_PriceProximity()\n+        {\n+            var currentPrice = _bar.Close;\n+            var limitPrice = _order.LimitPrice;\n+            var threshold = 0.02;\n+\n+            var delta = System.Math.Abs(currentPrice - limitPrice);\n+            var percentDelta = delta / limitPrice;\n+            var isNearLimit = percentDelta \u003c threshold;\n+\n+            if (delta \u003c 0 || percentDelta \u003c 0)\n+            {\n+                throw new System.InvalidOperationException(\"Invalid proximity\");\n\u003c/code_context\u003e\n\u003cissue_to_address\u003e\n**suggestion:** The negative checks on `delta` and `percentDelta` are logically impossible given how they are computed.\n\nSince `delta` is `Math.Abs(currentPrice - limitPrice)` and `percentDelta` is `delta / limitPrice` with `limitPrice \u003e 0`, neither value can be negative unless you get NaN/Infinity. That makes this exception branch effectively unreachable and easier for the JIT to optimize away. If you want to validate the proximity logic, it would be more meaningful to check for NaN/Infinity or domain issues like `limitPrice \u003c= 0` instead.\n\n```suggestion\n            var delta = System.Math.Abs(currentPrice - limitPrice);\n\n            // Validate domain before performing division\n            if (limitPrice \u003c= 0 ||\n                System.Double.IsNaN(limitPrice) || System.Double.IsInfinity(limitPrice) ||\n                System.Double.IsNaN(currentPrice) || System.Double.IsInfinity(currentPrice))\n            {\n                throw new System.InvalidOperationException(\"Invalid proximity\");\n            }\n\n            var percentDelta = delta / limitPrice;\n            var isNearLimit = percentDelta \u003c threshold;\n\n            // Validate the computed proximity\n            if (System.Double.IsNaN(percentDelta) || System.Double.IsInfinity(percentDelta))\n            {\n                throw new System.InvalidOperationException(\"Invalid proximity\");\n            }\n```\n\u003c/issue_to_address\u003e\n\n### Comment 3\n\u003clocation path=\"benchmarks/BarUpdateBenchmark.cs\" line_range=\"45-54\" /\u003e\n\u003ccode_context\u003e\n+            };\n+        }\n+\n+        [Benchmark]\n+        public void OnBarUpdate_HotPath()\n+        {\n+            var time = _bar.Time;\n+            var close = _bar.Close;\n+            var volume = _bar.Volume;\n+\n+            var hasCash = _account.CashValue \u003e 0;\n+            var hasPnL = _account.RealizedPnL != 0.0;\n+\n+            var isWorking = _order.OrderState == OrderState.Working;\n+            var limitPrice = _order.LimitPrice;\n+\n\u003c/code_context\u003e\n\u003cissue_to_address\u003e\n**issue (performance):** Several locals are computed but never used, which can lead to the benchmark being partially or fully optimized out.\n\nIn `OnBarUpdate_HotPath`, `hasPnL` and `isWorking` are computed but never used, so the JIT may eliminate them and distort the benchmark. Please route these through a `Consumer`/BenchmarkDotNet `Blackhole` or otherwise make them observable so the work is preserved in the hot path.\n\u003c/issue_to_address\u003e\n~~~\n\n\